    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "First, let's check if the roots are actually \"coming out\" or if you've just repotted it too recently, as new root growth can look similar. If your fiddle leaf fig is indeed ready for repotting, gently remove the plant from its current pot, trim any dead or mushy roots, and place it in a new container that is only 1-2 inches larger in diameter to avoid root rot. Fill the new pot with high-quality, well-draining potting mix, ensuring the drainage holes are clear, and then firm up the soil around the base of the stem. Water the plant lightly after repotting and avoid moving it to direct sunlight or cold drafts for the first week to help it acclimate. Over time, once the new roots establish, your fiddle leaf fig should recover and thrive again.",
